Introduction¶

Background Information & Purpose¶

For our final tutorial, we will be analyzing the trends in streaming culture through a platform called Twitch. Created in 2011, Twitch continues to be used for live-streaming various types of entertainment, such as video game playthroughs, esport competition broadcasts, and more[1](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Twitch_(service)). Streamers, or users who stream, are able to earn money through the platform by joining either Twitch’s Partner or Affiliate program. However, Twitch has a very strict and rigorous set of criterion for streamers who desire to join the Partner program. As such, we will focus on the Affiliate program instead since becoming an Affiliate is much easier than becoming a Partner.

For a streamer to join the Affiliate program, streamers need to have at least 50 followers, and within the last 30 days, the streamers must:

  • Stream at least 500 total minutes (8.4 hrs) of broadcast
  • Have 7 unique broadcast days
  • Obtain an average of 3 or more concurrent viewers[2](https://affiliate.twitch.tv/)

Consequently, for a streamer who wants to earn some money through Twitch, they would need to join the Affiliate program. And to do so, they would need to find and live-stream content that other Twitch users would like to watch and be entertained by. Therefore, our group decided to analyze the different trends in streaming culture so that we are able to discover what streaming content is most viewed and well-liked. Ultimately, we hope to give valuable information for people like streamers who would like to attract more viewers and earn money through the Twitch streaming services.

Datasets/Packages/Libraries¶

Using this dataset from Kaggle.com, we will extract the Top 20 most popular games for each month from January 2016 to October 2021; the popularity will be based on the rank of the games for each month. We decided to only look at the Top 20 most popular games for each month because too much data points will clobber our graphs which will decrease readability and reduce the effectiveness of our analyses. Additionally, we will use the game_genres.csv file for our analysis as it provides us the genres for each game that was categorized by Twitch. We manually inputted the data in the game_genres.csv file because we could not find any existing dataset that gives the information that we needed and we could not extract the information from Twitch’s website. Lastly, we will also be using the following Python packages/libraries for this tutorial:

Data Cleaning & Tidying¶

Before we begin the analysis, we will need to clean up the dataset so that we can better analyze the data. In order to do so, we will do the following:

  1. Import the necessary datasets and convert them into workable code.
    • We will use Pandas’ read_csv() function to convert the dataset files into data frames -- Pandas’ version of tables.
    • We will be referencing the data frame with the data from Twitch_game_data.csv the most. For the sake of simplicity, we will refer this data frame as **data**.
    • For the other csv files, please refer to the code below for the names of the respective data frames.
  2. Clean the data within the data frame.
    • We will remove “ hours” from the Hours_Streamed column in **data** so that we can convert the value into a number instead of keeping the hours as a string type.
  3. Merge the genres for each game from **genre_df** with the games in **data**.
    • We will need to use the genres for our analyses later.
  4. Aggregate the month and year columns into a new column called “Date” in **data**.
    • By combining the columns, we can filter and analyze the rows much easily.
  5. Replace Unicode characters within the “Game” column of **data** for consistency.
  6. Remove all other rows in **data** if the “Rank” value is less than 20, since we are only analyzing the top 20 games for each month.
  7. Reorder the rows in **data** by the dates.
  8. Remove any rows with missing values in **data**.
In [ ]:
TOP_N = 20

# Convert .csv datasets to DataFrames
data = pd.read_csv("Twitch_game_data.csv", sep=',')
monthly_df = pd.read_csv("Twitch_global_data.csv", sep=',')
genre_df = pd.read_csv("game_genres.csv", sep=',')

# Clean data

    # Remove " hours" from Hours_Streamed column
    # Convert Hours_Streamed column to int
data["Hours_Streamed"] = data["Hours_Streamed"].map(lambda x : x.rstrip(" hours"))
data["Hours_Streamed"] = pd.to_numeric(data["Hours_Streamed"])

    # Add game genres to each entry
data = pd.merge(data, genre_df, on="Game")

    # Aggregate Date
data["Date"] = data["Year"].map(str) + '-' + data['Month'].map(str)
data['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Date'], format='%Y-%m').dt.strftime('%Y-%m')

    # Replace Unicode characters
print("Unicode characters found: ", data["Game"].str.extract(r'(<.*>)', expand=False).unique())
''' 
<U+00E9> - e
<U+00DB> - U
<U+2212> - -
<U+72FC> - 狼
<U+4EBA> - 人
<U+6BBA> - 殺
<U+014C> - O
<U+016B> - u
'''
data["Game"] = data["Game"].str.replace(r'<U\+00E9>','e', regex=True)
data["Game"] = data["Game"].str.replace(r'<U\+00DB>','U', regex=True)
data["Game"] = data["Game"].str.replace(r'<U\+2212>','-', regex=True)
data["Game"] = data["Game"].str.replace(r'<U\+72FC>','狼', regex=True)
data["Game"] = data["Game"].str.replace(r'<U\+4EBA>','人', regex=True)
data["Game"] = data["Game"].str.replace(r'<U\+6BBA>','殺', regex=True)
data["Game"] = data["Game"].str.replace(r'<U\+014C>','O', regex=True)
data["Game"] = data["Game"].str.replace(r'<U\+016B>','u', regex=True)

    # Remove ranks past TOP_N
data = data.loc[data['Rank'] <= TOP_N]

    # Reorder by time
data = data.sort_values(by=['Month', 'Year'], ignore_index=True)

    # Remove missing values
data.dropna(inplace=True)

    # Date Dataframe for plots
dates_df = pd.DataFrame({'Date': np.sort(data['Date'].unique())})

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Let us recall the requirements for joining Twitch’s Affiliate program:

  • Have at least 50 followers
  • Within the last 30 days,
    • Stream at least 500 total minutes (8.4 hrs) of broadcast
    • Have 7 unique broadcast days
    • Obtain an average of 3 or more concurrent viewers

Because we are only suggesting what new streamers should stream in order to join the Affiliate program, we will mainly focus on tackling the issues of streaming at least 500 total minutes (or 8.4 hours) of broadcast and obtaining an average of 3 or more concurrent viewers within the last 30 days.

Twitch Top 20 Games: Total Games per Genre (2016 - 2021)¶

First, we will create a bar chart that will show us the total number of unique games for each genre across all the months between January 2016 and October 2021. This graph will tell us which genre has the most variety of popular games to choose from when streaming.

In [ ]:
# Get unique games
g_data = data.drop_duplicates('Game')
genre_counts = {}
count = 0
for i, r in g_data.iterrows():
    genre = str(r['Genre']).split(",")
    for g in genre:
        if g not in genre_counts:
            genre_counts[g] = 1
        else:
            genre_counts[g] += 1

        count += 1

# Make bar chart
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
genre_y = np.arange(len(genre_counts.keys()))
genre_labels = list(genre_counts.keys())

genre_c, genre_labels = zip(*sorted(zip(genre_counts.values(), genre_labels), reverse=True))
ax.barh(genre_y, genre_c, align='center')
ax.set_yticks(genre_y)
ax.set_yticklabels(genre_labels)
ax.invert_yaxis()
ax.set_xlabel('Number of Games')
ax.set_ylabel('Genres')
ax.set_title('Top 20 Twitch Games Across Jan 2016 to Oct 2021: Number of Distinct Games Per Genre')
fig.set_size_inches(10, 10)

for i, v in enumerate(genre_c):
    ax.text(v + .5, i + .2, str(v))

plt.show()

Observation: With a whopping count of 98, Action has the highest number of unique popular games from January 2016 to October 2021, as followed by Adventure Game and RPG with 71 and 51 counts respectively. New streamers may want to consider streaming Action-type games since they will not easily get bored of the genre!

Twitch Top 20 Games: Total Average Viewership vs Genre (2016-2021)¶

Next, we will create three line graphs that will tell us the total average viewership for each genre across all the months between January 2016 and October 2021. Since there are 30 different genres, we decided to split the genres into chunks of 10 because having a line graph of 30 different lines would reduce the readability of the graph and data. So, we created a line graph for each set of 10 genres. We also sorted the list of genres by the total average viewership in ascending order before splitting them into 3 groups. As such, the first graph gives the 10 genres with the least total average viewership, the second graph gives the middle 10 genres, and the third graph gives the last 10 genres with the highest total average viewership across all the months between January 2016 and October 2021. Ultimately, these graphs will tell us the sustainability and attractiveness of a genre from a viewer’s perspective.

In [ ]:
genre_list = list(genre_counts.keys())

genres_total_viewers = []

for genre in genre_list:
    data_by_genre = data.loc[data["Genre"].str.contains(genre)]
    genres_total_viewers.append((genre, data_by_genre['Avg_viewers'].sum()))

genres_total_viewers.sort(key=lambda x: x[1])

genre_chunks = list()
chunk_size = 10

for i in range(0, len(genres_total_viewers), chunk_size):
    genre_chunks.append(genres_total_viewers[i:i+chunk_size])

colors = cm.turbo(np.linspace(0, 1, 10))

for genres in genre_chunks:
    plt.figure(figsize=(25, 10))
    
    for (c, genre) in zip(colors,  [g[0] for g in genres]):
        data_by_genre = data.loc[data["Genre"].str.contains(genre)]
        grouped = data_by_genre.groupby(["Date"])["Avg_viewers"].sum().reset_index()
        view_data = dates_df.merge(grouped, how='left', on='Date')  
        plt.plot_date(
            view_data['Date'],
            view_data['Avg_viewers'],
            fmt='-o',
            label=genre,
            color=c)

    plt.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))
    plt.title('Twitch Top 20 Games Across Jan 2016 to Oct 2021: Total Average Viewership Per Genre')
    plt.ylabel('Total Average Views')
    plt.xlabel('Dates')
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    ax = plt.gca()
    ax.get_yaxis().set_major_formatter(
        tick.FuncFormatter(lambda x, p: format(int(x), ',')))
        
    plt.grid()

Observations: Right off the bat, we noticed that there were some genres with discontinuities in their lines. For instance, in the first graph, we can see that the Platformer suddenly appears in August 2020 (08/2020) and then disappears after September 2020 (09/2020). Discontinuity in a line means that the games belonging to that specific genre did not rank in the top 20 for the month. So relating back to the discontinuity of Platformer, it means that Platformer games became popular enough to rank at least top 20 for the months of August and September in 2020, but were not popular priorly or afterwards.

Another cool thing to note is that we now have our top 10 most popular genres based on the viewership of games belonging to the specific genres! Interestingly, the number one genre is Action, again! Since Action has the highest number of unique popular games, it may explain why it is also the number one genre based on viewership (more Action-type games = more people who know of Action-type games = more people encouraged to watch Action-type game streams).

Average Stream Time Per Genre¶

Starting from this section, we will only use the top 10 most popular genres given from the previous section for better readability and analysis.

In this section, we will create another line graph to demonstrate the total average stream time per genre for each month between January 2016 and October 2021. This graph will help us to visualize how many hours are invested by Twitch streamers in each genre; it gives us an idea on how popular a genre is from the perspective of a streamer. Additionally, it can help new streamers to figure out the competition for each genre, as more hours invested for a genre could also mean that more streamers would focus on that particular genre.

In [ ]:
top_10_genres = [g[0] for g in genre_chunks[2]]

plt.figure(figsize=(25,10))

for genre in top_10_genres:
    data_by_genre = data.loc[data["Genre"].str.contains(genre)]
    grouped = data_by_genre.groupby(["Date"])["Hours_Streamed"].sum().reset_index()

    stream_data = dates_df.merge(grouped, how='left', on='Date')  
    
    plt.plot_date(
        stream_data['Date'],
        stream_data['Hours_Streamed'],
        fmt='-',
        label=genre)

plt.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))
plt.xticks(rotation = 90)
plt.title("Total Monthly Stream Hours for Twitch Categories (2016 - 2021)")
plt.xlabel("Date (Month - Year)")
plt.ylabel("Hours")
plt.grid()

Observations: Once again, Action remains as the number one genre! Although, between March 2020 and August 2021, Action struggles to stay on top, while Shooter battles Action for the first place! Beginning of February 2020, we can see that Shooter rapidly gains stream time, and in the next month, it reaches where Action is. Afterwards, Shooter dominates Action in stream time and stays in first place before going back down to second place in September 2020. Essentially, we can presume that Action is a popular genre for both streamers and viewers! So, new streamers should be aware that Action-type gaming streams can attract both viewers and competition from other streamers…

Hypothesis Testing and Machine Learning¶

In [ ]:
for genre in top_10_genres:   
    plt.figure()

    print("################ {} ################".format(genre))
    data_by_genre = pd.DataFrame(data.loc[data["Genre"].str.contains(genre)])
    data_by_genre["Hours_Streamed_Per_Streamer"] = data_by_genre["Hours_Streamed"]/data_by_genre["Streamers"]
    data_by_genre["Avg_viewers_Per_Streamer"] = data_by_genre["Avg_viewers"]/data_by_genre["Streamers"]

    res = smf.ols(formula='Avg_viewers_Per_Streamer~Hours_Streamed_Per_Streamer', data=data_by_genre).fit()
    print('Parameter Model Values:\n{}\n'.format(res.params))
    print('Parameter P-Values:\n{}'.format(res.pvalues))

    plot = data_by_genre.plot.scatter(
            x='Hours_Streamed_Per_Streamer',
            y='Avg_viewers_Per_Streamer',
            figsize=(12,7), 
            grid=True,
            title='Top {} Games: Average Viewers vs Hours Streamed (2016 - 2021)'.format(genre),
            xlabel="Hours Streamed",
            ylabel="Average Viewers"
        )

    corr= data_by_genre.corr().abs()
    s = corr.unstack()
    so = s.sort_values(kind="quicksort")
    p = res.params

    # generate x-values for your regression line (two is sufficient)
    x = np.arange(1, data_by_genre["Hours_Streamed_Per_Streamer"].max()+1, step=1)

    # plot regression line on the same axes, set x-axis limits
    plot.plot(x, p.Intercept + p.Hours_Streamed_Per_Streamer * x, color="red")

    plt.show()
    print("\n")
